"Bonanno tells the story of Julia Martinez, a college student whose father died in a bicycling accident. In the days after his death, she withdrew from her mother and had trouble sleeping. But soon she emerged. She went back to school, where, even if sometimes she felt “sad and confused,” she didn’t really want to talk to her friends about the death. Within a few months, she was thriving. Her mother, though, insisted that she was repressing her grief and needed to see a counsellor, which Julia did, hating every minute of it." (The New Yorker, February 2010)
___________
As this article goes on to say, don't punish the resilient ones. Grief manifests differently in people. The average presence of grief is marked at two years. The house plant in the background (whose name I cannot remember) was given to me by an employer after my dad passed in college. I carry it with me in every office as a reminder of my dad's work ethic and a reflection of my growth beyond his presence here on earth. .

Researchers from the University of Toronto created a "dietary portfolio" for cholesterol reduction that included a low fat diet, high in plant sterols, soy protein, solube fiber, and almonds and tested this diet against lovostatin for its ability to reduce cholesterol and inflammation in patients with high cholesterol.

The diet reduced cholesterol and inflammation (hs-CRP) by 28.6% and 28.2%, respectively compared to the statin that reduced cholesterol by 30.9% and 33.3%. One might say, "why not take the statin". Statins can deplete Vitamin D and CoQ10, they significantly increase the risk of diabetes, and can lead to memory problems and muscle pain.

The diet, you might lose weight, feel better, look better, and reduce your risk of almost every other chronic disease.

#naturalmedicine #dietfirst

I used to be embarrassed of my wide-set hips and the way my stomach formed too many rolls of skin whenever I sat down. When I was younger I hated how large my breasts were, how they weighed me down and changed my posture, and the way they stretched my skin. I would look at myself in the mirror and tell myself how ugly my smile was, I despised the way my teeth protruded outward, the gaps between my teeth and that they didn't align up perfectly straight. I hated that I didn't have the same features as my friends, and I hated that in the eyes of society, I was ugly. I felt ugly. I told myself I was ugly all the time, for a long time. I tried everything I could to change what I was and how I looked. I wanted to be anything other than myself. Our culture has conditioned us to believe that we have to maintain our bodies in a certain manner to be accepted, to be beautiful, and even to be loved. It's all a load of shit. How I look, or how my body is shaped does not define the amount of love that I deserve. 👑 ...Read the rest of this blog on body acceptance at riseofthewoman.com #riseofthewoman #bodyacceptance
